Groups representing Khoi people are going up against a large property developer. CAPE TOWN - Groups representing Khoi people are going up against a large property developer. The Liesbeek Leisure Properties Trust wants to turn the River Club area in Observatory, Cape Town, into residential, retail and office space. It's a project worth about R4-billion. But, indigenous people and civil society groups want national heritage status for the land. READ:Â Khoi and San communities to reap benefits of rooibos industry Various groups are saying the area is of significant ecological and historical importance. Khoi people lived along the rivers here, before the land was appropriated in the 1650s. The groups now want provincial and national heritage protection for Two River Urban Park.